Now,
 $f(x)=\frac{x^2-6x+6}{2x-4}
=\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{x^2-6x+6}{x-2}=\frac{1}{2}\cdot(x-4)+\frac{-2}{x-2}
=x-4-\frac{2}{x-2}.$
Thus $f(x)$ has vertical asymptote $x=2,$ and oblique asymptote $y=x-4.$</think>
 <answer>Since $g(x)$ has the same vertical asymptote as $f(x),$ its denominator must have $(x-2)$ as one of its factors. Therefore, $g(x)=\frac{ax^2+bx+c}{x-2}.$ Now examine the asymptotes of $g(x):$ the slope of its oblique asymptote is $\frac{a}{1}=a,$ and the point of intersection with $y$-axis is $(0, c).$ Since the oblique asymptotes of $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ are perpendicular, $a=-1.$</answer>

